    <h3 class="article-header-text">What is Kanji?</h3>
    <p class="article-text">
        Kanji is one of the three scripts used to write the Japanese
        language. Unlike Hiragana and Katakana, the other two scripts,
        kanji is a logographic script, meaning that its letters
        (generally) represent meaning instead of sound.
    </p>
    <p class="article-text">
        Kanji was imported to Japan from China by the way of Korea
        sometime in the 5th century. As such, to know the origins of
        kanji, you have to understand the origins of Hanzi, as the script
        is called in Chinese.
    </p>
    <p class="article-text">
        Hanzi was developed by the Chinese around 3000 years ago. Back
        then, it was a rudimentary writing system used to carve into bones
        and other hard objects, such as turtle shells, and did not contain
        as many characters as it does today.
    </p>
    <p class="article-text">
        As Chinese civilization developed, their writing system did as
        well, leading to thousands of new characters being introduced into
        it. It was this more complete form of Hanzi that later would
        become kanji.
    </p>
